XXXVIII. In speaking of painting one must not omit the famous story about Lepidus. During his Triumvirate‚‘2 when entertained by the magis- trates of a certain place, he was given lodging in a house buried in trees3 and the next day he complained to them in threatening language that he had been robbed of sleep by the singing of the birds; however the authorities had a picture of a large snake made on an extremely long strip of parchment and fixed it up round the wood, and the story goes that this at once frightened the birds into silence, and that subsequently it was possible to keep them in check.

XL. It is recorded also that Pamphilus, the Pausias. teacher of Apelles, not only painted in encaustic but also taught it to Pausias of Sicyon, the first artist who became famous in this style. Pausias was the son of Bryetes, and started as his father's pupil.
